\dropcap{H}ow do private expressions of thanks spread through social groups that produce public goods, and what role does that appreciation play in the formation and maintenance of those goods? Questions about the function and structure of gratitude 
%expressions 
are part of an enduring scientific discussion about the origin and maintenance of human cooperation \cite{smith_theory_1777, simmel_faithfulness_1996,mccullough_is_2001, simpson_roots_2018}. Pragmatically, this science also explains the existence of large-scale public goods, which are often sustained by volunteers. %, who contribute the equivalent of 61 million full-time workers annually \cite{volunteers_what_2021}.  % removed due to reviewer suggestions
For example, tens of millions of volunteers \footnote{https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Wikipedia:Wikipedians} have created and sustained Wikipedia, a free resource of global knowledge \cite{benkler_wealth_2006, reagle_wikipedia_2020, jemielniak_common_2020} that has become a basic building block for education \cite{okoli_wikipedia_2014}, elections \cite{salem_wikipedia_2023}, financial markets \cite{hinnosaar_wikipedia_2023}, and artificial intelligence \cite{baack_critical_2024}. %  and contributes \$42 billion dollars to the U.S. economy alone per year \cite{brynjolfsson_how_2019}. 
By investigating the role of gratitude expressions in large-scale cooperation, scientists can explain how volunteer-supported public goods come into being and also inform their effective creation and maintenance.

%% things to get across:
%% gratitude as an exchange versus a feeling
%% expressions of gratitude - expressions of appreciation
%% private gratitude versus public recognition

Scientists who study cooperation describe large-scale endeavors like Wikipedia as examples of indirect reciprocity, where people contribute resources to those who never helped them and may never directly return the favor \cite{fulk_connective_1996, benkler_wealth_2006}. Experiments have shown that people contribute to public goods when they can expect downstream benefits, which are coordinated through reputation \cite{gallus_fostering_2016} and self-efficacy \cite{bandura1977self}. Receiving gratitude acts as a powerful validation that sustains intrinsic motivation, making individuals feel effective (competence) and connected to others (relatedness) \cite{ryan2000self}. Gratitude transforms a solitary act of editing into a socially valued contribution, reinforcing users to continue contributing labor to the public good.

Public goods also rely on upstream reciprocity, where people ``pay it forward'' by providing resources to others who are unlikely to help them back, regardless of any reputational benefits \cite{nowak_upstream_2007}. Psychologists have hypothesized that this upstream reciprocity occurs after people respond to the gratitude they feel by directly thanking back the person who helped them \cite{simpson_roots_2018, horita2016transient, nowak_upstream_2007}. Gratitude induces positive affect and spreads through social networks, where recipients are compelled to interact more positively with others under emotional contagion \cite{fowler2008dynamic, barsade2002ripple}. Second, receiving gratitude signals a social norm that expressing appreciation is a standard and valued behavior in the community, encouraging recipients to conform to this practice \cite{tankard2016norm}. A single gratitude functions as a prospective catalyst for generalized reciprocity, initiating a cascade of appreciation that extends upstream beyond the direct reciprocity bonds \cite{gray2014paying, nowak_upstream_2007}.
% Yet scientists have also observed indirect, asymmetric structures of private gratitude, where people thank others upstream, outside of direct reciprocity bonds (maybe add citation). In one large-scale observational study, researchers found evidence that upstream thanks was twice as common as appreciation pairs \cite{spiro_networks_2016}.
Observational research on private appreciation systems finds that asymmetric, indirect structures of thanks are common, with upstream thanks occurring more often than reciprocal appreciation pairs \cite{spiro_networks_2016}. These patterns suggest a distinct, forward-looking pathway in which receiving thanks motivates people to give gratitude to others.



%JNM TODO above: fill in and adjust citations to more strongly match and support the argument

%% JNM TODO: adjust "Yet" to be clearer to name the puzzle or say outright that there's incongruent evidence or evidence that points in a direction that scientists have not considered as much

One challenge for observational research is that expressions of thanks are both a cause and an effect of reciprocity. Psychological accounts of interpersonal appreciation describe it as a way for people to feel and express gratitude when they receive a benefit from another. People express thanks to acknowledge that a consequential exchange has occurred and that they intend to pay it back \cite{bartlett_gratitude_2006}. In this account, feelings and expressions of gratitude function as a ``moral barometer'' for exchange and obligation, flowing backward in a relationship after value has been given and received \cite{mccullough_is_2001}. When applied to indirect reciprocity in simulations, the influence of giving on gratitude can leave a trail of thanks that follows on from the flow of contributions \cite{nowak_upstream_2007}. In this model, people who receive benefits feel good about them and express gratitude to acknowledge their indebtedness to the giver. When grateful-feelers also help others, the chain of reciprocity spreads through the group, followed by an after-image of gratitude expressions \cite{simpson_roots_2018}. Yet research on direct reciprocity has found that expressing gratitude strengthens bonds by causing givers to help even further \cite{riskin_expressions_2019, kong_because_2019}. Might exchanges of thanks serve as a cause of indirect reciprocity as well as an echo of it?

%  A parallel possibility is that private expressions of gratitude also directly cause cascades of further appreciation, potentially by influencing social norms, people's beliefs about what others expect \cite{tankard2016norm}. 

