% Collaborative endeavors such as Wikipedia are systems of generalized exchange. In these communal public goods, people who contribute knowledge expect to learn about areas where they do not have expertise, receiving benefits indirectly rather than just exchanging knowledge with people who edit the same articles as them. 

% structure: does gratitude follow on from an exchange, or can receiving gratitude influence other gratitude expressions?
% direction: does gratitude flow downstream or upstream  
% effects: what effect does that have on participation. 
% direction of appreciation

% Scholarship on the effects of appreciation have tended to focus either on private exchanges between pairs or on public recognition in organizations, rather than private exchanges in a system of indirect reciprocity.

% Within organizations, scientists have found that public appreciation supports cooperation through reputation, increasing the chance that a receiver of gratitude will gain benefits from third parties. These increases in reputation also cause gratitude-receivers to make further contributions to the group \cite{gallus_fostering_2016, simpson_roots_2018}.

%  Yet scientists have observed patterns of private gratitude that are not as easily explained by public reputation or reciprocity between pairs. In one large-scale observational study in the workplace, researchers found evidence that asymmetric structures were twice as common as reciprocity between pairs \cite{spiro_networks_2016}. 

% Beyond pairs of reciprocity, one enduring question for the science of gratitude has been how it shapes and responds to behavior within groups. In indirect and generalized reciprocity, people contribute within a group with the expectation that they will receive benefits from others in the group. 


%In this hypothesized forward cascade, the experience of receiving thanks itself makes people more likely to express appreciation in forward-facing cascades, then expressions of gratitude might be a partial contributor to the formation and maintenance of large-scale cooperation networks, not just a barometer of other forces that sustain them.

These questions about the function of private gratitude expressions have pragmatic implications for volunteer-supported public goods, since volunteers rarely receive direct rewards or reciprocity. One notable example of these public goods is Wikipedia, a multilingual encyclopedia available in over three hundred languages.\footnote{\url{https://meta.wikimedia.org/wiki/List_of_Wikipedias}, accessed July 1, 2020} Millions of Wikipedia contributors have coordinated to create the world's most consulted information source.\footnote{\url{https://www.alexa.com/siteinfo/wikipedia.org}, Accessed July 1, 2020} Maintaining this free, common resource requires indirect reciprocity from volunteers who pay forward the knowledge they have received in the hope that others' knowledge will provide them with value in turn \cite{benkler_wealth_2006}. While this indirect reciprocity is partially maintained through reputational rewards \cite{gallus_fostering_2016, restivo2014wiki, kriplean2008articulations}, Wikipedia also facilitates the exchange of private thank-you messages. By mid-2018, Wikipedia contributors were sending nearly seventy thousand of these private messages per month.
%% source: 2018-08-17-analyze-thanklove.ipynb and datasets/all_the_gratitude_data/gratitude_20180814.csv
%Because contributing to Wikipedia is skilled work with a high standard of quality, many editors leave soon after their first contribution, especially when their inexperienced edits are removed to maintain the quality of the encyclopedia \cite{halfaker_rise_2013}. 
If receiving private thanks influences how people contribute to public goods and how much they express upstream gratitude to others, encouraging appreciation on Wikipedia could help sustain and grow this valuable knowledge resource.

Wikipedia is a fruitful context for field experiments on the diffusion of gratitude expressions. In the social sciences, field experiments are used to validate theories in naturalistic settings and observe unexplained causal phenomena for further theory-building \cite{paluck_field_2014, cialdini_fullcycle_1980}. As a cooperative endeavor sustained through generalized exchange, Wikipedia provides a naturalistic setting in which upstream, private appreciation might occur. Finally, since the Wikipedia software hosts hundreds of distinct language encyclopedias, scientists can conduct parallel replications of a research question across multiple cultures and languages \cite{hill_studying_2017}. 

----------------------------------------------------------------------

Wikipedia also includes features for sending and receiving private appreciation. When someone receives a ``Thanks'' on Wikipedia, they receive a private alert on the Wikipedia website (Figure \ref{fig:thank.notification}), and an email (by default) from the sender. The message names the account that sent the expression of gratitude and identifies the specific contribution that merited thanks. Compared to public recognition on Wikipedia \cite{gallus_fostering_2016}, these messages of appreciation are private and are only easily visible by the recipient \cite{matias_kittens_2019}, ruling out reputation as a mechanism for their effects. The software behind Wikipedia also records the sender, receiver, time, and object of every expression of thanks sent between contributors \cite{goel_thanks_2019}. 

\begin{figure}[h]
    \centering
    \includegraphics[width=0.9\linewidth]{figs/notification-screenshot.png}
    \caption{Notification received by participants who received thanks}
    \label{fig:thank.notification}
\end{figure}

In a large-scale field experiment on Wikipedia, we tested the hypothesis that receiving thanks influences how people thank others and also influences how they contribute to generalized reciprocity. We designed this study in collaboration with liaisons from the Arabic, German, Persian, and Polish language communities, which collectively have over 27,000 monthly active contributors (Table \ref{table:participants}). Working with humans and machine learning models to identify newcomers and experienced editors %within languages 
whose contributors merited appreciation, we randomly assigned over fifteen thousand participants to be thanked by one of 313 volunteers or to be omitted from the thanking campaign. Over the next six weeks, we observed how long participants continued to contribute to Wikipedia, the labor hours per day after assignment, the rate at which they sent expressions of gratitude to others, and the network structure of those downstream thanks. 

\section*{Results}
We evaluated the intent-to-treat (ITT) effect of receiving thanks among $\Sexpr{prettyNum(nrow(participants), big.mark=",")}$ participants from August 2, 2019, through March 24, 2020. We pre-registered our analysis plan before data collection, including plans for multiple comparison adjustments \cite{holm_simple_1979}.\footnote{\url{https://osf.io/c67rg/}} Among active accounts, 55\% of newcomers and 46\% of experienced accounts met our criteria for contributions that merited thanks; they were consequently included in the study (Table \ref{table:participants}). This population includes all individuals randomly assigned to the treatment condition, regardless of whether they ultimately received a thank-you message from a volunteer. \footnote{Many assigned participants didn't receive thanks due to volunteer selection decisions, software errors, or account deletion.} Among the $\Sexpr{prettyNum(nrow(subset(participants, TREAT==1)), big.mark=",")}$ participants in the treatment group, volunteers chose to thank 31\% of newcomers and 43\% of experienced accounts (Table \ref{table:participants}). 


Across all four Wikipedia communities, being assigned to receive thanks caused participants to thank others $\Sexpr{prettyNum(exp(subset(all.results, model=="thanks sent" & lang == "all")$Estimate)*100 - 100, digits=2)}$\%  more than those in the control group (\textit{p}$=\Sexpr{prettyNum(subset(all.results, model=="thanks sent" & lang == "all")$pvalue, digits=2, scientific=FALSE)}$, Figure \ref{fig:combined}B, Table \ref{tab:itt_results}). Crucially, this increase was not driven by direct reciprocity: of the $\Sexpr{prettyNum(sum(treat.reciprocal.thanks.df$nonreciprocal.thanks.sent) + sum(treat.reciprocal.thanks.df$reciprocal.thanks.sent), big.mark=",")}$ thanks sent by participants in the treatment group, \Sexpr{prettyNum(sum(treat.reciprocal.thanks.df$nonreciprocal.thanks.sent)/ (sum(treat.reciprocal.thanks.df$nonreciprocal.thanks.sent) + sum(treat.reciprocal.thanks.df$reciprocal.thanks.sent))*100, digits=3)}\% 
were sent to someone other than the volunteer who thanked them. 
Only 
\Sexpr{prettyNum(100-sum(treat.reciprocal.thanks.df$nonreciprocal.thanks.sent)/ (sum(treat.reciprocal.thanks.df$nonreciprocal.thanks.sent) + sum(treat.reciprocal.thanks.df$reciprocal.thanks.sent))*100, digits=1)}\% 
of thanks followed a pattern of reciprocity.

Assignment to the thanks also increased the two-week retention of participants by $\Sexpr{prettyNum(subset(all.results, model=="retention" & lang == "all")$Estimate*100, digits=2)}$\% on average (\textit{p}$=\Sexpr{prettyNum(subset(all.results, model=="retention" & lang == "all")$pvalue, digits=2, scientific=FALSE)}$, Figure \ref{fig:combined}A, Table \ref{tab:itt_results}). Our manipulation check found that among $\Sexpr{prettyNum(subset(all.results, model=="manipulation check" & lang=="all")$n.size, big.mark=",")}$ survey-takers, being assigned to receive thanks increased the chance of someone remembering seven weeks later that they had received thanks (\textit{p}$<$0.0001). 


We also examined treatment effects on contributors' average daily labor hours during the observation period post-treatment (Table \ref{tab:labor_hours_per_day_results} ``all''). 
% untreated versus treated
Among all participants, being assigned to receive thanks caused participants to contribute \Sexpr{prettyNum(exp(subset(labor_per_day_results, subgroup == "all" & predictor == "TREAT1")$Estimate) * 100 - 100, digits=2)}\%
more daily labor hours than the control group (\textit{p}$=$\Sexpr{prettyNum(subset(labor_per_day_results, subgroup == "all" & predictor == "TREAT1")$pvalue, digits=2, scientific=FALSE)}). 
In this interaction model (Table \ref{tab:labor_hours_per_day_results} ``all---interaction''), higher levels of pre-treatment activity significantly amplified the effect of gratitude. For every hour of additional pre-treatment contribution per day, the effect of receiving thanks boosts the outcome by \Sexpr{prettyNum(exp(subset(labor_per_day_results, subgroup == "all" & predictor == "TREAT1:centered.labor.hours.per.day.pre.treatment")$Estimate) * 100 - 100, digits=3)}\% (\textit{p}$<$0.0001). 
For example, consider a treated participant who historically contributed just 5 minutes more per day than the average treated contributor. 
They experienced a \Sexpr{prettyNum(((exp(subset(labor_per_day_results, subgroup == "all" & predictor == "TREAT1")$Estimate + subset(labor_per_day_results, subgroup == "all" & predictor == "TREAT1:centered.labor.hours.per.day.pre.treatment")$Estimate * (5/60)) - 1) - (exp(subset(labor_per_day_results, subgroup == "all" & predictor == "TREAT1")$Estimate) - 1)) * 100, digits=1)}\% 
greater effect than it would have been for the average treated contributor, for a \Sexpr{prettyNum((exp(subset(labor_per_day_results, subgroup == "all" & predictor == "TREAT1")$Estimate + subset(labor_per_day_results, subgroup == "all" & predictor == "TREAT1:centered.labor.hours.per.day.pre.treatment")$Estimate * (5/60)) - 1) * 100, digits=2)}\% 
total increase in labor hours compared to the untreated group working on average levels. This suggests that gratitude acts as a reinforcement multiplier: it is effective for the average contributor but significantly more for those with established high-output activity levels.

% ($e^{0.10 + 0.70 \times 0.17}$)

