%\Sexpr{prettyNum(exp(subset(labor_per_day_results, subgroup == "all" & predictor == "TREAT1:centered.labor.hours.per.day.pre.treatment")$Estimate) * 100 - 100, digits=2)}\% increase after being thanked (\textit{p}$<$0.0001).

% 10 mins --> 13.8 mins (very skewed, small values so big boost is likely)

\begin{figure}[h]
    \centering
    \includegraphics[width=0.9\linewidth]{figs/interaction_effect_marginal_histogram.png}
    \caption{The change in post-treatment labor hours per day in relation to the change in centered pre-treatment labor hours per day for newcomers and experienced contributors (Table \ref{tab:labor_hours_per_day_results}). The histograms at the top represent the distributions of centered pre-treatment labor hours per day for newcomers and experienced contributors, respectively.}
    \label{fig:labor.hours.interaction}
\end{figure}


While more active contributors experienced larger effects on labor hours on average among all participants, this interaction was different for newcomers (n=\Sexpr{prettyNum(subset(labor_per_day_results, subgroup == "newcomer" & predictor == "TREAT1")$n.size, big.mark=",")}) and experienced editors (n=\Sexpr{prettyNum(subset(labor_per_day_results, subgroup == "experienced" & predictor == "TREAT1")$n.size, big.mark=",")}). In subgroup analyses (Table \ref{tab:labor_hours_per_day_results} ``newcomers'' vs. ``experienced''), there are distinct responses driven by opposing interaction effects (Figure \ref{fig:labor.hours.interaction}), where the interaction was negative among newcomers (Table \ref{tab:labor_hours_per_day_results} ``newcomer''), but positive among experienced contributors (Table \ref{tab:labor_hours_per_day_results} ``experienced'').

Treated newcomers spent \Sexpr{prettyNum(exp(subset(labor_per_day_results, subgroup == "newcomer" & predictor == "TREAT1")$Estimate) * 100 - 100, digits=2)}\% 
more time contributing per day to Wikipedia (\textit{p}$<$0.0001) than untreated newcomers working on average levels. The magnitude of this effect was lower for newcomers with higher pre-treatment activity levels: for every additional hour of pre-treatment contribution per day, the gratitude effect diminishes by \Sexpr{prettyNum(exp(subset(labor_per_day_results, subgroup == "newcomer" & predictor == "TREAT1:centered.labor.hours.per.day.pre.treatment")$Estimate) * -100 + 100, digits=2)}\% (\textit{p}$<$0.0001). 
For instance, a newcomer contributing 5 minutes more per day than the average experienced only a \Sexpr{prettyNum((exp(subset(labor_per_day_results, subgroup == "newcomer" & predictor == "TREAT1")$Estimate + subset(labor_per_day_results, subgroup == "newcomer" & predictor == "TREAT1:centered.labor.hours.per.day.pre.treatment")$Estimate * (5/60)) - 1) * 100, digits=2)}\% 
increase in labor hours due to the treatment relative to the control group. However, 49.7\% of newcomers contribute zero labor hours during the pre-treatment period, and 21.4\% of them contribute above the average (1.39 mins/day). Most newcomers contribute a similar amount of time to Wikipedia, with only 4.6\% editing the site for 5 more minutes a day than the average. This suggests that while gratitude is a powerful retention tool for the new community members, it has less additional marginal utility to those who have already established contribution habits.

% compared to untreated newcomers: exp(6.50573) =668.96 times (from 10mins to 60mins)
% compared to treated newcomers: exp(6.50573-1.3) = 182.31%
% the treated condition has less of a benefit than untreated

In contrast, a sub-group analysis of experienced contributors found an interaction in the opposite direction (\textit{p}$<$0.0001) but did not find a difference between treatment and control on average (\textit{p}$=$\Sexpr{prettyNum(subset(labor_per_day_results, subgroup == "experienced" & predictor == "TREAT1")$pvalue, digits=2, scientific=FALSE)}). The treated ones who worked every additional hour per day were motivated to contribute significantly more by \Sexpr{prettyNum(exp(subset(labor_per_day_results, subgroup == "experienced" & predictor == "TREAT1:centered.labor.hours.per.day.pre.treatment")$Estimate) * 100 - 100, digits=2)}\% than the untreated working at average pre-treatment activity levels (\textit{p}$<$0.0001). Due to this interaction, editors with higher levels of pre-treatment labor hours did experience a positive effect of being assigned to treatment. For example, an experienced editor contributing 5 minutes more per day than the average responded to the treatment with a significant \Sexpr{prettyNum((exp(subset(labor_per_day_results, subgroup == "experienced" & predictor == "TREAT1")$Estimate + subset(labor_per_day_results, subgroup == "experienced" & predictor == "TREAT1:centered.labor.hours.per.day.pre.treatment")$Estimate * (5/60)) - 1) * 100, digits=1)}\% increase in labor hours relative to the control group. However, similar to newcomers, 42.1\% of experienced contributors contribute zero labor hours during the pre-treatment period, and 15.8\% of them contribute above the average (2.77 mins/day). Most experienced contributors also contribute a similar amount of time to Wikipedia, with only 7.7\% editing the site for 5 more minutes a day than the average. This finding implies that for long-term community members, social appreciation does not revitalize low-activity users, but successfully reinforces and sustains the labor of editors who take on the most workload.



% Among all participants, the treatment effect on total labor hours varied substantially by pre-treatment activity levels. Among newcomers specifically, we found a substantial positive effect on total labor hours post-treatment (\textit{p}$<$0.001), indicating that receiving thanks led newcomers to spend more time contributing to Wikipedia in absolute terms. 



% Among the $\Sexpr{prettyNum(nrow(subset(participants, newcomer)), big.mark=",")}$ newcomers we included as participants in Arabic, German, and Polish Wikipedias,\footnote{We did not include Persian language newcomers in the study.} we did not find an effect from receiving thanks on the difference in daily labor hours over six weeks (\textit{p}$=$$\Sexpr{prettyNum(subset(all.newcomer.cace.df, model=="labor hours" & subgrou\textit{p}$=$="newcomer" & lang == "all" & factor=="iv1")$pvalue, digits=2)}$, Figure \ref{fig:combined}, Table \ref{tab:itt_results}). These complier-average causal effects are all consistent with the results of pre-registered intent-to-treat esimates (Table S1). 

% Across all four Wikipedia communities, being assigned to receive thanks caused participants to thank others at $\Sexpr{prettyNum(exp(subset(all.lang.results, model=="thanks sent" & lang == "all")$Estimate), digits=2)}$ times the rate of those in the control group (\textit{p}$=$$\Sexpr{prettyNum(subset(all.lang.results, model=="thanks sent" & lang == "all")$pvalue, digits=1)}$, Figure \ref{fig:combined}B, Table \ref{tab:itt_results}) on average. Being assigned to receive thanks also increased the two-week retention of participants by $\Sexpr{prettyNum(subset(all.lang.results, model=="retention" & lang == "all")$Estimate*100, digits=1)}$ percentage points on average (\textit{p}$<$0.001, Figure \ref{fig:combined}A, Table \ref{tab:itt_results}). Our manipulation check found that among  $\Sexpr{prettyNum(subset(all.lang.results, model=="manipulation check" & lang=="all")$n.size, big.mark=",")}$ survey-takers, being assigned to receive thanks increased the chance of someone remembering seven weeks later that they had received thanks (\textit{p}$<$0.0001). Among the $\Sexpr{prettyNum(nrow(subset(participants, newcomer)), big.mark=",")}$ newcomers we included as participants in Arabic, German, and Polish Wikipedias,\footnote{We did not include Persian language newcomers in the study.} we did not find an effect from receiving thanks on the difference in daily labor hours over six weeks (\textit{p}$=$$\Sexpr{prettyNum(subset(all.lang.results, model=="labor hours" & lang == "all")$pvalue, digits=2)}$, Figure \ref{fig:combined}, Table \ref{tab:itt_results}).

\begin{figure}[h]
    \centering
    \includegraphics[width=0.95\linewidth]{figs/combined.plot.itt.png}
    \caption{ITT effects for (A) two-week retention of Wikipedia contributors and (B) thanks sent to others (model coefficients), and (C) labor hours per day after treatment, in subgroups of newcomers and experienced contributors from different communities: Arabic (ar), German (de), Polish (pl), and Persian (fa) marked by ISO 639-1 language codes. Error bars represent 95\% confidence intervals. Dashed lines indicate null effect (0 for percentage points, 1 for ratios).}
    \label{fig:combined}
\end{figure}

